Problem Statement.
Existing navigation systems stop at the entrance of heritage sites, leaving visitors without guidance to explore monuments, discover historical significance, or experience Nepal's cultural heritage in a structured and engaging way.

Nepal Tourism Statistics
Nepal welcomed 1.147 million international tourists in 2024, showing a strong recovery in tourism demand.
Source: https://tourism.gov.np/content/83/nepal-tourism-statistics-2024/

Tourism contributes approximately 7-8% of Nepal's GDP (direct and indirect contribution).
Source: https://nepalpromotetreks.com/blogs/nepal-tourism-statistics
Nepal has 10 UNESCO World Heritage properties, including 4 cultural heritage sites in Kathmandu Valley alone, each containing numerous monuments and temples.
Source: https://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/np/

These demonstrate that a large number of visitors could benefit from improved heritage-site navigation.
Supporting Evidence
Lack of Tourism Centres and Security
Tourism centers have been established in Nepal only in limited places. These centers provide different tourism services like information about pleasant places, tourism maps, exchanging foreign currency etc. for tourists. Due to limited tourist centers, there are possibilities for tourists to be cheated. In some places, tourists have lost even their lives. Thus the lack of tourism centers and proper security arrangements are a great deterrent to the development of tourism in Nepal.

Source: https://andjournal.in/2018/07/13/tourism-importance-prospects-and-challenges-with-special-reference-to-nepal/
Heritage sites should provide centralized visitor information.
UNESCO recommends that every heritage site should provide visitors with easily accessible information, including maps, navigation, transport details, accommodation, and cultural interpretation through a centralized platform. However, UNESCO also notes that surprisingly few World Heritage sites provide such accessible digital resources.
Source: UNESCO Sustainable Tourism Toolkit
https://whc.unesco.org/en/sustainabletourismtoolkit/guide5/

Digital technologies enhance cultural tourism experiences.
UN Tourism emphasizes that digital technologies play a vital role in improving cultural tourism by modernizing heritage interpretation, increasing visitor engagement, and delivering innovative educational experiences.
Source: Session number 3 of UN Tourism & UNESCO Conference Concept Note
https://webunwto.s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/imported_images/50679/unwto_unesco_istanbul_conf_concept_note_22.11.2018_en.pdf

Tourists require integrated navigation and information systems.
Research on Destination Information Management Systems concludes that tourists benefit significantly from integrated platforms that combine navigation, destination information, and visitor support into a single system.
Source:
https://arxiv.org/abs/1402.1243

Competitors:

1. HoneyGuide Nepal https://honeyguideapps.com/ — This is likely your strongest direct competitor if we're talking Nepal specifically. It's a curated guide to Nepal's cultural heritage and local experiences, featuring walking tours, temple histories, and ecological information, developed in Nepal with input from local historians, ecologists, and cultural experts. It's built specifically to turn a confusing walk through a heritage site into a rich cultural experience by explaining what a visitor is looking at and the stories behind carvings, statues, and rituals. This overlaps hard with your "information, history, memories" pillar — but it has no AR, no indoor-specific navigation, and no gamification/badge system as far as documented.
2. Nepal Heritage App (NHDP) https://nepalheritage.app/ — Run by the Nepal Heritage Documentation Project, this app documents individual heritage sites across the Kathmandu Valley and West Nepal, including how sites contribute to ritual practices and living cultural usage. This is more archival/documentation-focused than experience-focused — think "database" not "guided journey" — so it's a weaker direct competitor but a strong content/data source you could reference for credibility.
3. GPSmyCity (Kathmandu walks) https://www.gpsmycity.com — A generic global self-guided tour platform localized with Kathmandu-specific routes (e.g., an 8-stop, 2-hour Durbar Square walking tour). It uses built-in GPS navigation to guide users stop to stop and works offline. This is functionally close to your core navigation loop but has zero AR, zero quiz/badge mechanics, and zero indoor focus — it's an outdoor, city-scale tool, not a small-premise one like your campus scenario.
4. Kathmandu Durbar Smartphone App (self-guided GPS walking tour, sold via Viator/Marriott Bonvoy) https://www.nowthingstodo.com/activity/THDP7668/kathmandu/kathmandu-durbar-smartphone-app-self-guided-gps-walking-tour — Marketed explicitly as a mix between a walking tour, sightseeing, and a scavenger hunt, letting users move through Durbar Square at their own pace. The "scavenger hunt" framing is close in spirit to your milestone/badge idea, but it's a paid tourist product, not a tech platform with AR or AI video.
5. Lokalee (https://www.business.lokalee.app/) — A digital concierge app offering dining recommendations, experiences, and attraction tickets, which also lists a Kathmandu Heritage Trail walking tour. It's a broader lifestyle/booking app with tours as one feature among many — not a focused competitor, but shows up in the same discovery space.
6. Saarang(https://saarang.com.np/) —Founded by three undergrad students (Sachin Dangi, Diwakar Rijal, Sushant Gaire) out of a college incubation centre, and a NYEF KTM Startup Awards 2022 nominee, Saarang's core mechanic is QR-coded storyboards physically installed at heritage sites — scan the code, get multilingual text/audio stories about that specific spot. They've placed roughly 100 boards across Kathmandu Valley within their first 10 months, and later expanded to Thamel, Lumbini, Pokhara, and Mustang, working with over 150 heritage sites and communities nationally.
